{{rewrite|date=June 2018}} [[File:Symonds Yat Rock View.JPG|thumb|200px|The Forest of Dean, the reported home of Beast of Dean]] The '''Beast of Dean''' is an animal said to live, or to have once lived, in the [[Forest of Dean]], [[Gloucestershire]], [[England]].<ref name = reed>Reed, Matthew and Naylor, Rhiannon and Lewis, Nick (2014) Feral big cats in rural Gloucestershire - reflecting on the possible presence of exotic animals in the English landscape.</ref> It was originally thought to resemble a [[wild boar]] (''Sus scrofa''), but abnormally large in size. At that time of its first sightings, wild boar were extinct in Britain.<ref name = goulding> Goulding, M. 2001.Possible genetic sources of free‐living Wild Boar (Sus scrofa) in southern England. Mammal Review: 31 </ref>
==History== Farmers from the village of [[Parkend, Gloucestershire|Parkend]] undertook an expedition to capture and kill the creature, in 1802 but found nothing. The animal they were hunting was reported to be a boar large enough to fell trees and hedges.
Beginning in the early 1990's a number of [[Phantom cat]]s were sighted in the Forest of Dean. <ref name = newton> Newton, M. 2005. Encyclopedia of Cryptozoology: a Global Guide. McFarland and Company Incorporated. London. p. 49</ref> The identity of these "Black Panthers" was thrown into further confusion in 2002 when a large Wild Boar with black fur was [[roadkill|killed]] in a collision along the [[A40 road (Great Britain)|A40]] near the town of [[Over, Gloucestershire|Over]]<ref name = newton/>.
==In fiction== In the science-fiction television series ''[[Primeval (TV series)|Primeval]]'', the Beast of Dean turns out to be a [[gorgonops]]id that arrived in the present day through a wormhole leading to the [[Permian]] period.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/review/story/0,,2010183,00.html|title=Saturday night feast of big, big beasts|last1=Flett|first1=Kathryn|last2=|first2=|date=11 February 2007|website=[[The Observer]]|publisher=|access-date=|quote=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070219224609/http://observer.guardian.co.uk/review/story/0%2C%2C2010183%2C00.html|archivedate=19 February 2007|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref>
