{{For|the 1931 film|The Street Song}}
'''''Gassenhauer nach Hans Neusiedler (1536)''''', commonly known as '''''Gassenhauer'''''<ref>The title is a colloquial archaic [[German language|German]] word originally meaning lively pieces of dance music, and later used for popular songs like operetta schlager during the early record era.</ref> ({{IPA-de|ˈɡasn̩ˌhaʊ̯ɐ|pron}}), is a short piece from [[Carl Orff]]'s [[Schulwerk]]. As the full title indicates, it is either an arrangement of, or inspired by, a much older work by the [[lutenist]] [[Hans Neusidler]] from 1536. It (along with several other pieces) is in fact credited to Orff's longtime collaborator, [[Gunild Keetman]], on at least one recent release of the Schulwerk.<ref>{{cite web|title=Orff-Schulwerk, Volume 1: Musica Poetica, Celestial Harmonies 13104-2|url=http://harmonies.com/releases/13104.htm}}</ref> As with many other pieces from the [[Schulwerk]], it has been used multiple times on television, radio, music, and in films, including the films ''[[Badlands (film)|Badlands]]'' (1973), ''[[True Romance]]'' (1993) (in a re-worked version by [[Hans Zimmer]]), ''[[Ratcatcher (film)|Ratcatcher]]'' (1999), ''[[Finding Forrester]]'' (2000), ''[[Monster (2003 film)|Monster]]'' (2003), and, most recently, Michael Moore's ''[[Capitalism: A Love Story]]'' (2009) and ''[[The Simpsons]]''′ 22nd-season episode "[[The Scorpion's Tale]]" (2011). The piece was used as the theme music for an afternoon radio program also titled ''Gassenhauer'' on the classical music station [[WCLV]] in [[Cleveland, Ohio]], in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Francis|first=Mark|title=Street Song / Gassenhauer: A 500 Year History|journal=Evergreen American Orff-Schulwerk Association Chapter Newsletter|year=2010|volume=34|issue=1|page=3|url=http://www.evergreenorffchapter.com/eocnews341.pdf|accessdate=June 6, 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113202156/http://www.evergreenorffchapter.com/eocnews341.pdf|archivedate=November 13, 2013|df=}}</ref> The piece also has clear influences on the 1940s golden-age Argentine Tango ''vals Caballero de la luna'' by instrumentalist Enrique Rodríguez<ref>https://tango.info/Z0000635824.</ref>

== Covers ==
[[Hans Zimmer]]'s piece "You're So Cool", from his musical score to ''[[True Romance]]'' (1993), is based on this composition.

